  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">CO-Scaling up DRR in Burundi</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The DRR program started in 2017 with a grant from the Belgian Cooperation for a pilot project in the provinces of Bubanza and Makamba. In 2019 the project attracted the attention of the DUE, which decided to finance an expansion of the current project to11 provinces. According to the wish of the DUE, the program is complementary to an IOM intervention financed under the same budget line and extended over the national territory.
The program#s goal is to improve the resilience of target communities and the expected impact is to have 66 local communities (in 11 provinces) capable of preventing, responding and mitigating the catastrophes# impact. It is based on 4 pillars:
1. Creation of DRR knowledge diffused till the lowest levels of the territorial organization (hills and communes) and easily applicable in case of emergency. Knowledge is transmitted using learning methodologies adapted to the target populations.
2. Establishment of communal and collateral disaster risk prevention platforms in the intervention zones, while ensuring their effective operation and the autonomy of these platforms. The action will ensure the development and implementation of action plans for each platform.
3. Creation of an Early Warning System, with information about weather alerts translated in Kirundi, exposed in practical terms for farmers and ultimately transmitted to people with a telephone that can receive SMS and transmit them to farmers. This without using the internet but the simple national phone network.
4. Prevent risks and increase households&apos; financial capacities to absorb shocks at the hilly level (the closest to the real needs of the population). This through:
- Sensitization of the population to good spatial planning and semi-urban agglomerations, combined with interventions (61 million BIF / commune) to correct the damagedone in the past;
- Interventions to increase the resilience of populations: AGR, facilitation of savings groups, linking the population with MFIs and health insurance, direct cash transfers, promotion of good agricultural practices.</narrative>
  </description>
